Adelani Adepegba, Abuja The Federal Road Safety Corps has confirmed that four of its personnel who were abducted by bandits had been rescued by security agencies. They were part of the 10 officials kidnapped in Nasarawa State on Monday. The Corps Public Education Officer, ACM Bisi Kazeem, confirmed the development on Tuesday. The PUNCH had reported that 26 FRSC officers were attacked while traveling from Sokoto and Kebbi States for a training programme at FRSC Academy, Udi on Monday. While two were killed, 10 were unaccounted for, eight escaped unhurt, while six were injured. Kazeem, however, said seven of the attacked personnel were currently receiving treatment in Abuja, adding that six kidnapped victims were yet to be rescued. He revealed that the deceased would be buried according to their religion,  adding that necessary arrangements had been made concerning their funerals. He said, “The Corps Marshall appreciated the effort of the Department of State Services, Army and the police for their prompt effort in ensuring  the rescue of four out of the 10 abducted personnel.” He assured that the corps would continue to work closely with security agencies to effect the rescue of the other victims and justice on the hoodlums. Meanwhile, five persons abducted in Tunga Maje community in the Federal Capital Territory last Thursday, have regained their freedom. The FCT police spokesman,  DSP Anjuguri Manzah, confirmed that they were released on Tuesday. Copyright PUNCH.
